-- Swedish FSA to give its view on capital requirements on Thursday
-- By Johan Ahlander
-- Mon May 05, 2014 09:23AM EDT
-- None



STOCKHOLM, May 5 (Reuters) - The Swedish Financial Supervisory Authority (FSA) will present its view on future capital requirements for Swedish banks on Thursday this week.

The Swedish government has said it wants capital requirements to be tightened and has asked the FSA to present a roadmap for regulations going forward. The FSA will give its position on measures, such as the countercyclical capital buffer, capital adequacy for systemically important institutions, mortgage risk-weight floors and financial institutions individual capital requirements under Pillar 2. The FSA is responsible for macroprudential supervision as well as the supervision of individual institutions in Sweden.  The FSA will publish its views at 0600 GMT on Thursday. A press briefing will be held at 0800 GMT.